article.description: Tina Charles scored 21 points and grabbed 14 rebounds to lead No. 1 Connecticut to a 77-48 victory over South Carolina on Sunday.
article.headline: UConn improves to 11-0 for third straight year with win over South Carolina
article.linkText: Charles rebounds from poor play to lead UConn
article.story:
COLUMBIA, S.C. -- Tina Charles was back to dominating the lane for No. 1 Connecticut.

Charles scored 21 points and grabbed 14 rebounds to lead the Huskies past overmatched South Carolina, 77-48, on Sunday.

The win helped Connecticut start 11-0 for the third straight season. UConn ended a long road trip that started on Dec. 14 at Madison Square Garden against Penn State and continued in Cancun, Mexico, for a three-game tournament the next week.

"I think sleeping in our own beds and playing in our own gym is hopefully going to give us a boost," Moore said. "It's been a tough road trip."

Charles, the 6-foot-4 standout center, had struggled in her last two games scoring just nine and eight. On Sunday, she got her team going, keying an early 18-3 run to take control.

Charles was 10-for-14 from the field and forced South Carolina to look to the outside for points.

About the only thing Charles botched was her attempt at a slam in the second half. She broke free on a steal and looked to have a clean try at the jam. However, the ball slipped out of her hand.

"I thought I had legs in order for me to get up there and do it," Charles said, laughing. "But I just didn't have the legs. Heavy legs."

Maya Moore added 15 points and Renee Montgomery 13 for the Huskies. UConn heads home to face Hartford on Wednesday.

South Carolina (6-5) lost its 21st straight to a ranked opponent. First-year coach Dawn Staley had tasted success at every level of basketball, yet has endured blowouts to Stanford and Connecticut the past two weeks.

"There are some things that happened in the game today that make you feel good about the team," Staley said. "And there are some things that do not make us feel good."

Staley had to be talking about the 22 turnovers, twice as many as Connecticut's total, and the poor first half shooting. The Gamecocks missed 11 straight two-point shots during one stretch.

But Staley pointed to Connecticut colleague Geno Auriemma as the blueprint for building a championship team and was glad for her team to see what it takes.

Auriemma wondered after his team's workout Saturday if it would show a bit of rust from a holiday break.

The Huskies -- and a sizeable following who showed up at the Colonial Life Arena -- put those fears to rest.

Of course, Charles and Moore were in the middle of it. Charles started things with an inside bucket, then Moore hit two straight baskets for UConn's first lead, 6-4. Charles added two more baskets, sandwiched around Montgomery's 3-pointer.

Moore closed the surge with a long-distance shot of her own and the Huskies were ahead 18-7.

And Connecticut kept the pressure on high. During one stretch, the Gamecocks missed 11 straight 2-point shots. Their only points during the last 9 minutes of the opening half came on Samone Kennedy's 3-pointer with 1:58 to go.

Charles had 14 points and 10 rebounds in the opening half. Moore had 12 points at the break.

Women's basketball has rarely been a big draw at South Carolina's six-year-old arena. However, the Huskies brought out a good-sized following from around the region. People waved "Go UConn" signs and snapped photos of the team during timeouts.

Staley, South Carolina's first-year coach, hopes to create that same atmosphere for the Gamecocks.

She'll need to find players like Charles and Moore.

Auriemma will have things to fix. South Carolina matched Connecticut for much of the second half and the Huskies tied a season-low for points.

He's glad for two things: his team's steady play and a flight back to Connecticut.

"That's a long time to live out of a suitcase and in and out of hotels and airports," Auriemma said. "And now we get a chance to get home."
